default1.6.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSome housing associations have seen an increase in voids, with particular difficulties in letting family homes e.g. 3 bed flats and houses in rural locations. One member, 
defaultEstuarydefault points to a 38% increase in 
defaultvoids in the first four months of 2013/14 compared to the same period the previous year, stimulated by transfers responding in part to welfare reform. 
default2.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe trends already outlined are likely to continue, with increased costs and bad debts, and reduced income. There will continue to be uncertainty over how tenants will respond both in the short and longer term. 
default2.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultHousing associations are likely to have to
default increase the number of evictions for non-payment of rent as well as dealing with the consequences of uncertainty around direct payments. 
default3.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe biggest impact has been the increased risk of family financial hardship with greater pressure on household budgets. The emotional impact and increased stress, particularly for vulnerable groups is not
default to be underestimated, as the following case studies show.
default3.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn particular, customers with disabilities have needed additional support in requesting DHP from their local authority or reviewing their options where they live in adapted housing. Those with fami
defaultlies who have been allocated a particular size of house by the local authority but now face the ‘bedroom tax’ reduction in their housing benefit have struggled to understand and cope with this.
default default3.3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultNorth Herfordshire Homesdefault reports that 676 of their 8,000 gene
defaultral needs tenants are affected by the ‘bedroom tax’, with 119 deemed to be under-occupying by two rooms or more. Arrears have increased for 409 (62%) of those affected, averaging £10.80. 14 possession orders have been obtained and two eviction warrants sou
defaultght for these cases. 150 of 
defaultNorth Herfordshire Homes’default tenants are waiting to downsize, but only 38 have been able to. 161 households are unable to move due to rent arrears or a possession order being in place. 
default3.4.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultFor those in the examples, the likely outcomes are that the costs to the tax payer will far outweigh the relative saving through imposing the ‘bedroom tax’, and do not 
defaultnecessarily make better use of our stock. Affected tenants have to make choices about ho
defaultw money is spent where previously those choices were made for them. These decisions become more acute when there simply is not enough money to cover some very basic outgoings. This will become more acute when direct payment is implemented.   
default&#xa0;defaultCase studiesdefault&#xa0;defaultA lives in a 3B and is deemed to be under occupying by 2 bedrooms with a 25% deduction in HB. He suffers from multiple sclerosis and in the absence of any family support receives 24 hour care from a professional carer. His carer only receives 5 hours pai
